raw:
The image shows a screenshot of an online survey questionnaire. The questions are as follows:

1. Trust coverage - A checkbox question with radio buttons labeled 'Strongly disagree', 'Disagree', 'Neutral', 'Agree', and 'Strongly agree'.
2. Mood impact - Similar to the first question, this is another checkbox question asking about the impact of the Olympics on one's mood.
3. Age - A fill-in-the-blank text field where participants are expected to enter their age.
4. Follow by age - A select dropdown with options 'Very closely', 'Somewhat', 'Only highlights', 'Not much', and an empty 'Select...' option.
5. Employment status - Another select dropdown question with options 'Student', 'Full-time', 'Part-time', 'Self-employed', and 'Not currently working'.
6. Watch time - A slider question asking for the amount of time spent daily on Olympics content, with a range from 1 to 10 hours.
7. Attention text_mid - A select dropdown question with options 'Very closely', 'Somewhat', 'Only highlights', 'Not much', and an empty 'Select...' option.
8. Country satisfaction - A slider question asking for satisfaction with one's country's Olympic performance, with a range from 1 to 10.
9. Future interest - A select dropdown question with options 'Very likely', 'Likely', 'Unsure', 'Unlikely', and an empty 'Select...' option.
10. Favorite moment - A fill-in-the-blank text field where participants are expected to describe their favorite Olympic moment.
11. Next - A button that presumably leads to the next page of the survey.

The survey is partially completed, as indicated by the blue checkmarks next to questions 3, 5, and 6. It appears that the participant has selected 'Full-time' for employment status, 'Somewhat' for attention text_mid, and 'Very likely' for future interest. The age field is not filled in, and the watch time slider is set to 1 hour. The survey also contains a section titled 'Olympic Survey', which seems to be a placeholder or title for the survey rather than a question.

The bottom of the screenshot shows a navigation bar with options to go back, select some questions for this item, and move to the next page. There is also a message about moving to the next page once all questions are answered.
